receptor types activate at 37\u00b0C","Heat receptors respond to mechanical pressure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct response is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ecold receptors activate between 10-43\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E. Cutaneous cold receptors are most active in this temperature range, using TRPM8 channels to detect cooling. Their firing rate increases as temperature decreases below normal skin temperature (33\u00b0C) until reaching maximum activity around 25\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeat receptors activate below 25\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E - Heat receptors (TRPV1) activate above 43\u00b0C, not below 25\u00b0C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth receptor types activate at 37\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E - While some baseline activity occurs, this is not the optimal activation temperature for either receptor type\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECold receptors require sodium channel opening\u003C/strong\u003E - Cold receptors primarily use TRPM8 channels, not sodium channels, for temperature detection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeat receptors respond to mechanical pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Heat receptors are specifically thermosensitive and do not respond to mechanical stimuli\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese specialised thermoreceptors allow precise temperature detection across different ranges, contributing to thermal regulation and temperature sensation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thermoreceptors detect temperature changes through specific ion channels called transient receptor potential (TRP) channels."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Chapter 49; pg. 622. Available at: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95243"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95243"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:42:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:42:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes"